# Architecture and Design

Structural quality rules. Apply when designing modules, writing classes, or reviewing pull requests. Complements `@coding-standards.mdc` (style) and `@review-and-quality.mdc` (rubric).

## SOLID principles

### S - Single Responsibility
- Every class, module, and function has **one reason to change**.
- If you need "and" to describe what something does, split it.

### O - Open/Closed
- Open for extension, closed for modification.
- Use interfaces, strategy pattern, or plugins rather than editing existing code.

### L - Liskov Substitution
- Subclasses must be usable wherever the parent is used without breaking behavior.
- If a subclass overrides to do nothing or throw, use composition instead.

### I - Interface Segregation
- Do not force classes to implement interfaces they don't need.
- Prefer many small, focused interfaces over one large "god" interface.

### D - Dependency Inversion
- Depend on abstractions (interfaces), not concrete implementations.
- Inject dependencies; do not instantiate them deep inside business logic.

## Clean architecture

- Business/domain logic must **not depend on** frameworks, databases, or UI.
- Keep the core domain free of infrastructure concerns (HTTP, SQL, file I/O).
- Use dependency injection to wire layers together.
- Separate data models by layer: request/response DTOs != domain entities != DB schemas.
- **Dependency Rule**: source code dependencies point **inward only** (infra -> app -> domain).

## DRY / YAGNI / KISS

- **DRY**: Don't repeat logic. Extract and reuse. But don't over-abstract similar-looking code that serves different purposes.
- **YAGNI**: Don't build for hypothetical future requirements. Build what's needed now.
- **KISS**: Prefer the simplest solution that meets the requirement.

## Code smells to prevent

Never introduce these. When refactoring, actively remove them.

### Bloaters (too big)
- **Long method**: Keep under ~30 lines; extract helpers.
- **Large class**: Split into smaller, focused classes (SRP).
- **Primitive obsession**: Don't use raw `string`/`int` for domain concepts; use value objects (`Email`, `Money`, `UserId`).
- **Long parameter list**: > 3 params = use a parameter object.
- **Data clumps**: Groups of data that always appear together become a class/struct.

### Coupling problems
- **Feature envy**: Method uses more data from another class than its own. Move it.
- **Inappropriate intimacy**: Classes accessing each other's internals. Use interfaces.
- **Message chains**: `a.getB().getC().getD()` violates Law of Demeter. Use delegation.
- **Middle man**: Class that only delegates. Remove or inline unless it adds value.

### Change preventers
- **Divergent change**: One class changed for many reasons. Split by reason.
- **Shotgun surgery**: One change = edits across many classes. Consolidate.

### Dispensables (remove these)
- **Duplicate code**: Extract shared logic into a reusable function/module.
- **Dead code**: Delete unreachable code, unused variables, unused imports, unused functions.
- **Lazy class**: Too little to justify existence. Inline it.
- **Speculative generality**: No abstractions "just in case." YAGNI.

### OOP abusers
- **Switch on type**: Use polymorphism instead of `switch`/`if-else` on object type.
- **Refused bequest**: Subclass ignores most inherited methods. Use composition.
- **Temporary field**: Fields only set in certain scenarios. Extract into a separate class.

## How to verify

- During review, check each changed class/module against the SOLID checklist.
- Look for new smells in the diff (especially long methods, primitive obsession, feature envy).
- Run `./scripts/verify.sh`; lint rules catch some smells (e.g. complexity, unused code).
- If a refactor is needed, create a separate task/commit for it (don't mix with feature work).

## When NOT to apply

- Throwaway prototypes or spikes: pragmatism over purity; document the tech debt.
- Scripting or glue code: simple scripts don't need DI or layered architecture.
- Performance-critical hot paths: sometimes inlining or coupling is justified. Document with an ADR or comment explaining why.
- Third-party code: don't refactor vendored libraries; wrap or adapt instead.
